Introduction¶

The objective of this project is to develop models capable of accurately predicting whether an email is likely to be a spam and/or phishing attempt or a legitimate communication. Phishing and spam attacks represent a significant and growing threat in the cybersecurity landscape, through these attacks users can be deceived into clicking on malicious links that could compromise personal information or install malware on their systems. The models developed below are capable of analyzing the email’s text and domain of the embedded link. Using machine learning, I aimed to create a solution that could classify emails as either spam, phishing or safe with a high degree of accuracy.

The models used include, the ChatGPT-4 LLM and four machine learning models, Logistic Regression, Gradient Boosting, Decision Trees, and Random Forest Classifier were tested and evaluated to determine the most effective algorithm for spam and phishing email detection. The ChatGPT-4 LLM was selected due to its processing capabilities, the Logistic models were chosen for their ability to handle classification tasks and their varying strengths in handling complex data relationships.

EDA Summary¶

  1. There are no missing values in the dataset.
  2. The main variable of focus is the label and label_num variable, label=ham and label_num=0 is safe, label=spam and label_num=1 is spam.
  3. Emails have an average of 1,223 characters with a maximum of 22,073 and a minimum of 11.
  4. 75% of emails have a length below 1,254 characters.
  5. In terms of length, there are slight differences in length between spam and not spam emails. The mean email length for spam is 1,223 while safe emails is 977.
  6. The dataset is unbalanced with 3,672 safe emails and 1,499 spam emails.

Assembling Email Training Datasets¶

In [12]:
def count_tokens(text):
    encoding = tiktoken.get_encoding("cl100k_base")  
    tokens = encoding.encode(text) 
    return len(tokens)
In [13]:
Email_training_data_spam=Emails[Emails['label'] == "spam"].sample(n=5)
Email_training_data_ham=Emails[Emails['label'] == "ham"].sample(n=5)
Email_training_dataset=pd.concat([Email_training_data_spam,Email_training_data_ham])
Email_training_dataset=Email_training_dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)

Email_training_dataset=Email_training_dataset.drop(columns=["Unnamed: 0","label"])

while(count_tokens(Email_training_dataset['text'].str.cat(sep=''))>4000):
    Email_training_data_spam=Emails[Emails['label'] == "spam"].sample(n=5)

    Email_training_dataset=pd.concat([Email_training_data_spam,Email_training_data_ham])
    Email_training_dataset=Email_training_dataset.sample(frac=1).reset_index(drop=True)

Performing Text Analysis Training and Testing With ChatGPT 4.0¶

In [112]:
for index, row in Email_testing_dataset.iterrows():
    response = client.chat.completions.create(
        model="gpt-4",
        messages=[
            {"role": "system", "content": "You are an Email Spam Detector. You will be provided a JSON list of sample labeled emails, the labels are 0 for not spam and 1 for spam. After being provided the training list, you will be provided a dataset to label if it is spam or not."},
            {"role": "system", "content": "Provide answers in JSON format with no line space included. THe JSON headers will be label_num(only 0 and 1 is acceptable), confidence(0 to 1) and reasoning. You will provide exactly 1 JSON row in response to each question and will adhere to the mentioned heaaders"},
            {"role": "system", "content": f"The following is the training data: {Email_training_dataset.to_json()}, no response is needed for this, this is just for you to learn so don't reply to this"},
            {"role": "user", "content": f"The following is the data you will analyze and respond to: {row["text"]}"}
        ]
    )
    js = json.loads(response.choices[0].message.content)

    df_js=json_normalize(js)

    Email_testing_dataset.at[index, 'ChatGPT Label Guess'] = df_js['label_num'].values[0]
    Email_testing_dataset.at[index, 'confidence'] = df_js['confidence'].values[0]
    Email_testing_dataset.at[index, 'reasoning'] = df_js['reasoning'].values[0]

Aplying Feature Engineering¶

After taking into account the relevance of features in the dataset and their correlations to the Phishing variable, the following columns were chosen to be kept in the dataset with all others being removed:

  • Phishing
  • URLLength
  • DomainLength
  • IsDomainIP
  • CharContinuationRate
  • NoOfLettersInURL
  • LetterRatioInURL
  • NoOfDegitsInURL
  • DegitRatioInURL

Phishing EDA Conclusions¶

  1. There are a total of 57 columns, 42 are of integer type, 10 are of float type and 5 are of object type
  2. The key feature of the dataset is the Phishing variable
  3. Dataset is slightly skewed towards more Phishing data, there are approximately 135,000 safe emails(1) and 101,000 Phishing emails(0)
  4. The most negatively correlated features to safe emails are SpacialCharRatioInURL, qty_url_slashes, DegitRatioInURL, and LetterRatioInURL. The higher these numbers the less safe the email.
  5. The 4 most positively correlated features to safe emails are URLSimilarityIndex, HasSocialNet, HasCopyrightInfo, HasDescription

Feature Scaling¶

Initializing and training the model¶

In [72]:
param_grid = {
    'C': [0.01, 0.1, 1, 10],
    'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'],
    'solver': ['liblinear'],
    'class_weight': ['balanced', None]
}

lr = LogisticRegression()

grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=lr, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1)

Results¶

Conclusion¶

The Spam model was manually checked for accuracy using a validation dataset. Each Phishing model was assessed based on performance metrics such as Mean Squared Error (MSE), R-squared, and cross-validation accuracy. All models demonstrated exceptional results, consistently achieving high accuracy rates. The balanced datasets used for both training and testing ensured that the models did not suffer from class imbalance, further strengthening the reliability of the results. Among the models, Random Forest and Gradient Boosting showed the best performance, both achieving high predictive accuracy while maintaining computational efficiency.

The key features selected for model training—such as domain reputation, URL structure, and the presence of suspicious characters in the link—proved to be highly relevant in distinguishing between phishing and non-phishing emails. These variables were either strongly positively or negatively correlated with the likelihood of an email being a phishing attempt, providing clear signals that the models could leverage to make accurate predictions. This indicates that machine learning can effectively capture subtle patterns in email characteristics that might otherwise be difficult for traditional methods to detect.

As cybersecurity threats continue to evolve, the use of machine learning to detect phishing emails offers a scalable and adaptive approach to enhancing security infrastructure. This project demonstrates that machine learning models, when properly trained with relevant and well-curated features, can significantly improve phishing detection, providing a valuable tool for organizations looking to defend against increasingly sophisticated phishing campaigns. Furthermore, the results from this project serve as a foundational step in developing more advanced systems capable of addressing a broader range of cybersecurity threats in real-time.

In conclusion, while this project serves as an initial exploration into using machine learning for spam and phishing detection, the promising results lay the groundwork for future enhancements. More granular features, such as email content analysis, user behavior, and multi-modal approaches combining both email and website data, could be incorporated to improve detection accuracy even further. As both spam and phishing attacks become more sophisticated, the integration of machine learning models into automated cybersecurity systems offers a proactive and efficient means of safeguarding users and organizations from these growing threats.
